WEBVTT

00:01.535 --> 00:04.403
A daring escape to freedom.

00:04.405 --> 00:06.572
ALCOCK: Hewas not just
risking his own life,

00:06.574 --> 00:08.140
but all of his
friends and family.

00:08.142 --> 00:10.876
[ Whistle blares,
brakes squeal ]

00:10.878 --> 00:14.179
The amazing machine
that changed the world.

00:14.181 --> 00:16.648
He really wanted to create
something phenomenal

00:16.650 --> 00:19.685
that had never been seen.

00:19.687 --> 00:23.489
And a bizarre battle
rocks the Big Top.

00:23.491 --> 00:26.759
The fireman threatened to
burn down the circus tent.

00:26.761 --> 00:29.428
♪♪

00:29.430 --> 00:31.930
These are
the "Mysteries at the Museum."

00:31.932 --> 00:37.102
♪♪

00:37.104 --> 00:40.439
The majestic shoreline
of Encinitas, California,

00:40.441 --> 00:42.341
is a surfer's paradise.

00:42.343 --> 00:45.477
So it's no surprise that
these were the very breaks

00:45.479 --> 00:48.647
that the Beach Boys
immortalized in their hit song,

00:48.649 --> 00:50.849
"Surfin' U.S.A."

00:50.851 --> 00:52.117
And just inland

00:52.119 --> 00:55.654
is a place dedicated to
another Encinitas icon,

00:55.656 --> 00:57.923
the Bobby Riggs Tennis Museum.

00:57.925 --> 01:01.593
♪♪

01:01.595 --> 01:03.762
Located inside a tennis club,

01:03.764 --> 01:05.831
this unique display pays tribute

01:05.833 --> 01:09.368
to one of this city's most
famous sporting heroes --

01:09.370 --> 01:14.773
the 1939 world tennis champion,
Bobby Riggs.

01:14.775 --> 01:18.510
On display is a junior
championship trophy Riggs won

01:18.512 --> 01:20.179
when he was only 12...

01:20.181 --> 01:21.346
a member's tie from

01:21.348 --> 01:24.249
the All England Lawn Tennis
and Croquet Club,

01:24.251 --> 01:26.351
better known as Wimbledon,

01:26.353 --> 01:28.854
and a bronze statue
upon which are etched

01:28.856 --> 01:32.090
some of his finest
career achievements.

01:33.828 --> 01:36.528
But among the triumphant
pieces of memorabilia

01:36.530 --> 01:38.664
is an item that
recalls an episode

01:38.666 --> 01:41.099
mired in controversy
and scandal.

01:41.101 --> 01:45.137
MILLIKEN:
The artifact is 28 inches tall
and 12 1/2 inches wide.

01:45.139 --> 01:47.072
It weighs about 12 ounces.

01:47.074 --> 01:50.042
It consists of a metal frame
and strings.

01:50.044 --> 01:53.278
It's a pretty well-known piece
of sporting equipment.

01:53.280 --> 01:56.849
♪♪

01:56.851 --> 01:59.418
WILDMAN: This tennis racket
took center court

01:59.420 --> 02:03.055
in a monumental matchup
that defined a generation.

02:03.057 --> 02:06.291
MILLIKEN:
This is a story about
determination, skill,

02:06.293 --> 02:07.893
and the fight for equality.

02:07.895 --> 02:12.364
♪♪

02:12.366 --> 02:14.766
WILDMAN:
It's the early 1970s.

02:14.768 --> 02:17.002
In the world of
international tennis,

02:17.004 --> 02:21.507
an acrimonious conflict is
brewing between women and men.

02:21.509 --> 02:23.642
MILLIKEN: Tennis was a hugely
popular sport,

02:23.644 --> 02:24.877
and it kept getting bigger

02:24.879 --> 02:26.845
as a result of the
rise of television.

02:26.847 --> 02:30.115
And women were really finally
beginning to get attention.

02:30.117 --> 02:33.285
WILDMAN: But while male stars
are earning big bucks,

02:33.287 --> 02:36.054
women make just pennies
in comparison.

02:36.056 --> 02:39.124
MILLIKEN: The prizes were
shockingly different.

02:39.126 --> 02:41.126
Women tennis players
could be paid

02:41.128 --> 02:43.128
thousands of dollars
less than men.

02:43.130 --> 02:45.063
They must've been angry.

02:47.468 --> 02:50.335
WILDMAN: One player determined
to set things straight

02:50.337 --> 02:52.871
is 29-year-old Billie Jean King.

02:52.873 --> 02:56.275
Billie Jean King was
hands down, at the time,

02:56.277 --> 02:58.277
one of the best
players in the world.

02:58.279 --> 03:01.179
She had won Wimbledon,
she had won the US open,

03:01.181 --> 03:04.516
she had won multiple
Grand Slam events.

03:04.518 --> 03:06.652
I think she was the one
that felt obligated

03:06.654 --> 03:07.920
to do something about it.

03:07.922 --> 03:10.822
♪♪

03:10.824 --> 03:13.559
WILDMAN: One day, she gets
the perfect opportunity.

03:13.561 --> 03:16.962
In the spring of 1973,
she receives a challenge

03:16.964 --> 03:21.500
from a 55-year-old retired
male player named Bobby Riggs.

03:21.502 --> 03:24.336
MILLIKEN:
Bobby Riggs had once been
the best in the world.

03:24.338 --> 03:25.971
People knew him for his tennis,

03:25.973 --> 03:28.740
but they also knew him
because of his personality.

03:28.742 --> 03:31.310
He was a total chauvinist.

03:31.312 --> 03:34.546
WILDMAN:
Riggs is an outspoken opponent
of women's equality.

03:34.548 --> 03:36.381
MILLIKEN: He would say the most
ridiculous things.

03:36.383 --> 03:37.950
You know,
"Women belong in the kitchen,

03:37.952 --> 03:39.585
but they don't
belong on the court."

03:39.587 --> 03:43.388
He really didn't believe
there was a<i> shred</i> of equality

03:43.390 --> 03:46.325
between a man and a woman,
<i>especially</i> on the tennis court.

03:48.429 --> 03:50.262
King accepts Riggs' offer,

03:50.264 --> 03:53.865
but the champion knows that
to prove her point beyond doubt,

03:53.867 --> 03:55.467
she will have to win.

03:55.469 --> 03:58.337
King realized that
Riggs' absurdity

03:58.339 --> 04:00.105
actually was an opportunity.

04:00.107 --> 04:01.640
They would be on a large stage

04:01.642 --> 04:04.910
that would allow her to send
a message to the greater world,

04:04.912 --> 04:06.712
and I think she took it.

04:08.649 --> 04:10.816
WILDMAN: As the day
of the match draws near,

04:10.818 --> 04:14.219
interest in the epic
face-off starts to grow.

04:14.221 --> 04:17.155
MILLIKEN: I think people were
interested in this happening

04:17.157 --> 04:19.758
because the idea
of putting a woman

04:19.760 --> 04:23.261
right in the face of a guy
and watching them compete

04:23.263 --> 04:25.697
felt really powerful to women.

04:25.699 --> 04:28.667
The showdown even earns
a unique moniker.

04:28.669 --> 04:30.769
This match ended up
getting its own nickname --

04:30.771 --> 04:32.738
The Battle of the Sexes.

04:34.975 --> 04:37.676
WILDMAN: In preparation,
King meticulously studies

04:37.678 --> 04:40.612
her opponent's strengths
and weaknesses.

04:40.614 --> 04:42.547
Riggs, a former
champion himself,

04:42.549 --> 04:44.950
will be a tough adversary.

04:44.952 --> 04:49.388
But then King spies a chink
in his armor -- his stamina.

04:49.390 --> 04:52.257
MILLIKEN:
I think King felt like
she could wear him out

04:52.259 --> 04:54.826
through strategically
placed shots.

04:54.828 --> 04:56.862
WILDMAN:
If King can exhaust Riggs,

04:56.864 --> 04:58.930
she has a solid chance
of winning

04:58.932 --> 05:00.232
and will set an example

05:00.234 --> 05:03.935
not just for women athletes,
but for women everywhere.

05:03.937 --> 05:06.538
King knew that this was
much more than a tennis match.

05:06.540 --> 05:09.241
She felt the weight
of the women's movement

05:09.243 --> 05:10.542
on her shoulders.

05:10.544 --> 05:14.012
♪♪

05:14.014 --> 05:16.782
WILDMAN:
On September 20, 1973,

05:16.784 --> 05:20.419
30,000 fans pile into
the Houston Astrodome.

05:20.421 --> 05:24.122
More than 90 million people
tune in on their TVs.

05:24.124 --> 05:27.292
On the day of the match,
the energy was electric.

05:27.294 --> 05:29.294
WILDMAN:
King makes a splashy entrance,

05:29.296 --> 05:32.864
carried onto the court
by men clad in togas.

05:32.866 --> 05:35.600
Riggs, for his part,
arrives on a rickshaw,

05:35.602 --> 05:37.903
pulled by beautiful women.

05:37.905 --> 05:40.772
MILLIKEN: All of it was really
rather circus-like.

05:40.774 --> 05:42.674
It was a total spectacle.

05:42.676 --> 05:45.277
This is something that had
just not happened before,

05:45.279 --> 05:47.679
and the unpredictability
of what was gonna happen

05:47.681 --> 05:49.848
made it all the more charged.

05:49.850 --> 05:53.418
WILDMAN:
Finally, the moment King
has been waiting for arrives.

05:53.420 --> 05:56.154
MILLIKEN: The stakes could not
have been higher.

05:56.156 --> 05:58.990
Everything was on the line
for Billie Jean King.

05:58.992 --> 06:02.160
♪♪

06:02.162 --> 06:04.696
WILDMAN: At the outset,
King sticks to her strategy

06:04.698 --> 06:07.532
of trying to wear down
her opponent.

06:07.534 --> 06:10.202
But try as she might,
Riggs takes an early lead.

06:11.672 --> 06:14.573
I think she had a real moment
of vulnerability,

06:14.575 --> 06:16.842
of wondering whether or not
she was gonna pull this off,

06:16.844 --> 06:19.211
and whether or not she
had made the wrong call --

06:19.213 --> 06:22.114
maybe that she had
the wrong strategy.

06:22.116 --> 06:26.585
WILDMAN:
But as the match unfolds,
her tactic bears fruit.

06:26.587 --> 06:28.487
Riggs begins to make mistakes.

06:28.489 --> 06:32.424
♪♪

06:32.426 --> 06:34.493
MILLIKEN: Riggs started to make
some pretty silly shots,

06:34.495 --> 06:37.229
and missed shots
that he wouldn't have missed.

06:37.231 --> 06:40.799
There's no doubt that that gave
King a feeling of momentum,

06:40.801 --> 06:44.836
and a feeling of excitement
that she had a chance.

06:44.838 --> 06:47.239
WILDMAN: King pulls ahead
and wins the first set

06:47.241 --> 06:48.807
six games to four.

06:48.809 --> 06:52.477
♪♪

06:52.479 --> 06:55.480
Then, for the next two hours,
in game after game,

06:55.482 --> 06:58.183
she dominates her opponent.

06:58.185 --> 06:59.584
After three sets,

06:59.586 --> 07:02.120
Billie Jean King
emerges victorious.

07:02.122 --> 07:07.692
♪♪

07:07.694 --> 07:10.262
She wins
The Battle of the Sexes.

07:10.264 --> 07:13.031
The crowd went nuts.

07:13.033 --> 07:15.100
She threw her racket
into the air

07:15.102 --> 07:17.068
and had a real
moment of triumph.

07:18.372 --> 07:21.039
WILDMAN:
With millions of fans
watching on TVs

07:21.041 --> 07:22.340
across the country,

07:22.342 --> 07:25.010
it's exactly the
outcome King hoped for.

07:25.012 --> 07:27.679
MILLIKEN: Billie Jean King
did what she set out to do.

07:27.681 --> 07:30.315
She wanted to make a point --
she did it.

07:30.317 --> 07:31.583
And I think that in itself

07:31.585 --> 07:33.685
is an incredible moment
of history.

07:33.687 --> 07:36.221
♪♪

07:36.223 --> 07:38.089
WILDMAN: In the wake
of his crushing defeat,

07:38.091 --> 07:39.991
Riggs admits that
he underestimated

07:39.993 --> 07:41.259
his female opponent...

07:42.996 --> 07:45.697
...and the two rivals
bury the hatchet.

07:45.699 --> 07:48.667
King goes on to dominate
the professional tennis circuit,

07:48.669 --> 07:51.236
winning 39 Grand Slam titles,

07:51.238 --> 07:55.407
including six at Wimbledon
and four at the US Open.

07:55.409 --> 07:56.908
She even parlays her fame

07:56.910 --> 07:59.578
into forming
the Women's Tennis Association,

07:59.580 --> 08:02.747
an advocacy organization
for female players.

08:02.749 --> 08:05.116
MILLIKEN: As a result of King's
work in tennis,

08:05.118 --> 08:07.786
tennis has become
one of the few sports

08:07.788 --> 08:10.155
where men and women
are paid equally,

08:10.157 --> 08:11.990
and that's enormous.

08:13.493 --> 08:15.727
WILDMAN:
Today, the racket used by Riggs

08:15.729 --> 08:18.430
during the famous
"Battle of the Sexes" match

08:18.432 --> 08:21.132
is on display at
the Bobby Riggs Tennis Museum

08:21.134 --> 08:22.834
in Encinitas, California.

08:22.836 --> 08:24.870
It recalls the epic face-off

08:24.872 --> 08:28.173
that served up equal rights
on and off the court.

08:28.175 --> 08:31.343
♪♪

08:31.345 --> 08:33.378
In the heart of
central Wisconsin

08:33.380 --> 08:36.982
is a majestic rock formation
older than the Himalayas

08:36.984 --> 08:40.252
and jutting some
500 feet into the sky.

08:40.254 --> 08:42.754
This is the Devil's Doorway.

08:42.756 --> 08:46.524
Those brave enough to scale
these jagged lumps of quartzite

08:46.526 --> 08:50.161
are rewarded with panoramic
views of the valley below.

08:50.163 --> 08:52.497
And just north of these
breathtaking boulders

08:52.499 --> 08:54.165
is an institution dedicated

08:54.167 --> 08:56.668
to the wonders of
a manmade sort --

08:56.670 --> 08:59.170
the Circus World Museum.

08:59.172 --> 09:01.406
Built on the site of the
Ringling Brothers Circus'

09:01.408 --> 09:03.308
former winter base camp,

09:03.310 --> 09:05.277
this 64-acre complex

09:05.279 --> 09:07.579
is dedicated to
preserving the legacy

09:07.581 --> 09:09.948
of "The Greatest Show on Earth."

09:09.950 --> 09:12.884
Among the treasures
collected here is a pickup truck

09:12.886 --> 09:16.421
which once transported
the Human Cannonball,

09:16.423 --> 09:20.025
a ticket booth from
the early 20th century,

09:20.027 --> 09:24.629
and a tiny suit once worn by
a performer named Major Might --

09:24.631 --> 09:27.532
billed as the smallest
man in the world.

09:29.102 --> 09:31.569
But hidden among these
eye-catching relics

09:31.571 --> 09:34.439
is one that could be
easily overlooked.

09:34.441 --> 09:36.741
O'DONNELL: The artifact is
2 1/2 inches wide

09:36.743 --> 09:38.877
by 12 inches long.

09:38.879 --> 09:42.047
It is over 160 years old.

09:42.049 --> 09:45.150
On the right-hand side,
you'll see imagery of a giraffe,

09:45.152 --> 09:48.253
an elephant, a rhinoceros,
and a big cat.

09:48.255 --> 09:50.822
♪♪

09:50.824 --> 09:53.124
This aged circus bill is linked

09:53.126 --> 09:58.296
to one of the most bizarre
brawls the world has ever known.

09:58.298 --> 10:00.565
This is a story
about a brave mayor

10:00.567 --> 10:03.401
and a posse of fighting clowns.

10:03.403 --> 10:05.036
[ Glass breaking,
crowd screaming ]

10:05.038 --> 10:10.308
♪♪

10:10.310 --> 10:12.944
WILDMAN:
It's the mid-1850s.

10:12.946 --> 10:14.612
The Canadian city of Toronto

10:14.614 --> 10:17.615
is a wretched hive
of scum and villainy.

10:17.617 --> 10:21.853
O'DONNELL:
Toronto in the 1850s --
it was a Wild West vibe.

10:21.855 --> 10:24.289
It had a disproportionate
amount of taverns

10:24.291 --> 10:26.992
for the amount of people
and the size of the community.

10:26.994 --> 10:31.262
It meant that society had
ample supplies of alcohol

10:31.264 --> 10:34.866
and ample opportunities
for conflict to break out.

10:34.868 --> 10:36.801
And it did.

10:36.803 --> 10:38.336
WILDMAN:
Even the local police force

10:38.338 --> 10:41.306
and the fire department
are seen as part of the problem.

10:41.308 --> 10:43.608
They were notorious
for looking the other way.

10:43.610 --> 10:47.379
Corruption was in place,
and it was a tough town.

10:48.915 --> 10:52.417
WILDMAN: But one man thinks
he can clean up the chaos --

10:52.419 --> 10:56.554
the newly elected mayor,
33-year-old George Allan.

10:56.556 --> 10:59.124
George Allan was
ethical, ambitious,

10:59.126 --> 11:02.727
and determined to clean up
the corruption in his town.

11:02.729 --> 11:05.230
WILDMAN: And the mayor
is about to get his chance

11:05.232 --> 11:07.699
in the most colorful
fashion imaginable.

11:10.103 --> 11:15.240
On July 12, 1855,
trouble brews at a local bar.

11:15.242 --> 11:19.411
O'DONNELL:
This wasn't the average
disturbance at a local tavern.

11:19.413 --> 11:21.179
WILDMAN: Members of
the city fire department

11:21.181 --> 11:24.382
are squaring off
against an unlikely foe --

11:24.384 --> 11:26.518
a troupe of traveling clowns.

11:28.889 --> 11:32.490
The S.B. Howes' Star Troupe
Menagerie and Circus

11:32.492 --> 11:34.459
was in town.

11:34.461 --> 11:37.829
The circus clowns had performed
for two shows that day,

11:37.831 --> 11:40.732
and they were at the tavern
to blow off a little steam.

11:40.734 --> 11:43.201
WILDMAN: But what started
as a minor misunderstanding,

11:43.203 --> 11:44.569
swiftly escalated.

11:46.239 --> 11:47.772
O'DONNELL:
One of the local firefighters

11:47.774 --> 11:51.543
knocked the hat off
the star-performing clown.

11:51.545 --> 11:55.613
That clown thought that
he was owed an apology.

11:55.615 --> 11:58.550
An apology was not given.

11:58.552 --> 12:00.652
WILDMAN: At that,
an all-out brawl erupts.

12:00.654 --> 12:01.986
[ Glass breaking, yelling ]

12:01.988 --> 12:05.156
Surprisingly it's the
clowns who come out on top.

12:05.158 --> 12:06.658
O'DONNELL: It was epic --

12:06.660 --> 12:09.627
with the circus performers
coming out in the lead.

12:09.629 --> 12:12.430
They kicked
the firefighters' butts.

12:12.432 --> 12:15.100
♪♪

12:15.102 --> 12:17.268
WILDMAN: When the young mayor
hears what's happened,

12:17.270 --> 12:18.403
he's appalled.

12:19.906 --> 12:22.340
Mayor Allan had
to be frustrated ---

12:22.342 --> 12:25.343
a fight featuring
his fire department.

12:25.345 --> 12:27.479
But the matter isn't over yet.

12:29.916 --> 12:32.650
The next day,
on Friday the 13th of July,

12:32.652 --> 12:35.220
Mayor Allan is called
to another disturbance,

12:35.222 --> 12:38.056
this time at the
circus tent itself.

12:38.058 --> 12:40.125
He sends word to
the local militia

12:40.127 --> 12:42.727
and races to the scene
of the crime.

12:42.729 --> 12:44.162
When he reaches the fairgrounds,

12:44.164 --> 12:47.799
he's met by
an extraordinary sight.

12:47.801 --> 12:51.469
The firemen were trying
to tip over the circus wagons,

12:51.471 --> 12:54.205
trying to tear down the tent,
rip it apart.

12:54.207 --> 12:57.041
They also threatened to
burn down the circus tent.

12:59.346 --> 13:00.979
WILDMAN:
And that's not all.

13:00.981 --> 13:03.581
Members of the police
are also present,

13:03.583 --> 13:07.018
but instead of intervening,
they're simply watching.

13:07.020 --> 13:08.686
O'DONNELL:
The local police department

13:08.688 --> 13:11.256
should have been quelling
the violence.

13:11.258 --> 13:13.291
Instead, they were
cheering it on.

13:13.293 --> 13:14.959
WILDMAN:
Until the militia arrives,

13:14.961 --> 13:18.062
the only thing standing
in the way of utter carnage

13:18.064 --> 13:19.631
is Mayor Allan himself.

13:19.633 --> 13:22.867
All hell was about
to break loose in his town.

13:22.869 --> 13:28.640
♪♪

13:31.894 --> 13:35.662
It's July, 1855, in Toronto.

13:35.664 --> 13:38.532
A rather bizarre
riot is underway.

13:38.534 --> 13:40.434
The local fire squad is brawling

13:40.436 --> 13:43.404
with a troupe of
traveling circus clowns.

13:43.406 --> 13:46.440
Charged with the task
of quelling this rumpus

13:46.442 --> 13:48.108
is Mayor George Allan.

13:48.110 --> 13:52.112
So, can Allan control
this crowd of rowdy jokers?

13:52.114 --> 13:54.782
♪♪

13:54.784 --> 13:58.652
Allan desperately tries
to defuse the situation.

13:58.654 --> 14:00.053
O'DONNELL:
Mayor Allan was brave.

14:00.055 --> 14:04.358
He climbed up on the giraffe
wagon to address his people.

14:04.360 --> 14:07.895
He, alone, was trying to get
people to stop fighting.

14:07.897 --> 14:09.696
He tried to gain control.

14:09.698 --> 14:11.665
♪♪

14:11.667 --> 14:13.300
WILDMAN:
It's to no avail.

14:13.302 --> 14:16.804
The bloodthirsty mob
continues to raise hell.

14:16.806 --> 14:19.206
But then, the mayor's foresight
saves the day.

14:21.243 --> 14:25.379
The militia shows up,
and they stop the violence.

14:25.381 --> 14:27.614
WILDMAN:
The armed men quell the chaos,

14:27.616 --> 14:29.049
and as the dust settles,

14:29.051 --> 14:31.652
the scope of
the conflict becomes clear.

14:31.654 --> 14:34.021
The Big Top is in tatters.

14:34.023 --> 14:35.289
O'DONNELL:
The circus packed up

14:35.291 --> 14:37.858
what remaining equipment
had not been destroyed

14:37.860 --> 14:40.260
and headed off to the next town.

14:40.262 --> 14:41.762
WILDMAN:
As a result of the riot,

14:41.764 --> 14:43.664
Mayor Allan orders
an investigation

14:43.666 --> 14:45.699
of the police
and fire departments.

14:45.701 --> 14:49.570
Both are completely overhauled
to root out corruption.

14:49.572 --> 14:53.006
The story of the Circus Riot
becomes the stuff of legend.

14:53.008 --> 14:55.742
♪♪

14:55.744 --> 14:58.879
O'DONNELL:
This story has all the hallmarks
of a great movie.

14:58.881 --> 15:01.081
It has intrigue, corruption,

15:01.083 --> 15:04.351
a riot with clowns
and firefighters

15:04.353 --> 15:07.488
on Friday the 13th.

15:07.490 --> 15:11.992
WILDMAN: Today, an original ad
for the 1855 Summer Circus Tour

15:11.994 --> 15:14.361
is in the collection of
the Circus World Museum

15:14.363 --> 15:16.296
in Baraboo, Wisconsin.

15:16.298 --> 15:19.466
It acts as a reminder
of a one-of-a-kind rumpus

15:19.468 --> 15:24.104
and the bold mayor who put
a halt to the clowning around.

15:26.041 --> 15:27.975
In the heart of Berlin, Germany,

15:27.977 --> 15:31.745
is a spectacular mile-long
stretch of concrete wall

15:31.747 --> 15:35.449
adorned with with more
than 100 colorful murals.

15:35.451 --> 15:38.852
Dubbed the East Side Gallery,
these vibrant images

15:38.854 --> 15:41.955
are painted on the largest
still-standing section

15:41.957 --> 15:44.258
of the infamous Berlin Wall.

15:44.260 --> 15:46.627
And just a few minutes
away is an establishment

15:46.629 --> 15:50.163
named for the wall's most
notorious crossing point --

15:50.165 --> 15:51.932
the Checkpoint Charlie Museum.

15:53.502 --> 15:55.035
Visitors to the institution

15:55.037 --> 15:56.837
can learn of
the extraordinary means

15:56.839 --> 15:59.239
by which escapees
risked their lives

15:59.241 --> 16:01.308
in fleeing from
the communist East

16:01.310 --> 16:03.710
to the democratic West.

16:03.712 --> 16:05.412
Among the items on display

16:05.414 --> 16:09.316
is an ultralight airplane
that flew over the wall,

16:09.318 --> 16:12.953
an inflatable boat
used to paddle to freedom,

16:12.955 --> 16:16.890
and even a hollowed-out speaker
that once hid a human being.

16:19.061 --> 16:21.395
But of all the objects
on display,

16:21.397 --> 16:23.130
one more than any other

16:23.132 --> 16:26.333
illustrates the nature
of this historic barrier.

16:26.335 --> 16:30.571
ALCOCK: The artifact is made of
wood, plastic, and metal.

16:30.573 --> 16:34.741
It's 18 inches wide
and just under 5 feet long.

16:34.743 --> 16:36.109
It's a scaled-down version

16:36.111 --> 16:38.812
of train tracks
and barrier walls.

16:38.814 --> 16:42.849
♪♪

16:42.851 --> 16:44.184
WILDMAN:
This scale model

16:44.186 --> 16:46.687
of a section of
the Berlin Wall barricade

16:46.689 --> 16:50.324
recalls an incredible bid
to flee communist oppression.

16:50.326 --> 16:52.626
ALCOCK: This is a story about
a train conductor,

16:52.628 --> 16:54.962
a daring escape,
and a fight for freedom.

16:54.964 --> 17:02.769
♪♪

17:02.771 --> 17:05.238
WILDMAN: In the aftermath
of the Second World War,

17:05.240 --> 17:06.974
Europe is split in two.

17:06.976 --> 17:09.309
ALCOCK:
There was a division

17:09.311 --> 17:12.112
between the area occupied by
the Soviet Union

17:12.114 --> 17:14.047
and the areas
occupied by Britain,

17:14.049 --> 17:16.617
France, and the United States.

17:16.619 --> 17:18.452
WILDMAN: And nowhere is
this more apparent

17:18.454 --> 17:20.854
than in the city of Berlin.

17:20.856 --> 17:23.724
Located in the middle of
communist East Germany,

17:23.726 --> 17:26.827
one half of the city is
a tiny island of freedom

17:26.829 --> 17:29.396
in a sea of
totalitarian oppression.

17:31.100 --> 17:35.135
In 1961, the Soviets begin
to erect the Berlin Wall,

17:35.137 --> 17:38.705
a 12-foot-tall,
28-mile-long barricade

17:38.707 --> 17:40.807
through the center of the city.

17:40.809 --> 17:44.244
On the democratic western side,
life is flourishing.

17:44.246 --> 17:46.847
ALCOCK:
In the West, you had everything
that you would expect

17:46.849 --> 17:49.683
from a modern country
at that time.

17:49.685 --> 17:51.451
WILDMAN:
In the communist East, however,

17:51.453 --> 17:53.754
residents face extreme poverty,

17:53.756 --> 17:56.356
food shortages, and low wages.

17:56.358 --> 17:58.659
You struggled to
get your hands on

17:58.661 --> 18:02.295
what we would today consider
to be quite basic goods.

18:04.366 --> 18:05.732
WILDMAN:
Among those straining

18:05.734 --> 18:08.301
under the cruel yoke
of the communist regime

18:08.303 --> 18:12.072
is 28-year-old East Berliner
Harry Dieterling.

18:12.074 --> 18:15.942
ALCOCK:
Harry Dieterling was a very
loving, very caring man.

18:15.944 --> 18:18.545
He was married.
He had four children.

18:18.547 --> 18:20.947
WILDMAN:
Dieterling is desperate
to move his family

18:20.949 --> 18:23.150
to West Berlin and freedom,

18:23.152 --> 18:26.153
but crossing the border
is fraught with danger.

18:26.155 --> 18:27.487
ALCOCK:
The East German Police

18:27.489 --> 18:29.990
were put in place
to guard the wall.

18:29.992 --> 18:31.324
They were heavily armed.

18:31.326 --> 18:33.493
It was their job
to prevent anyone

18:33.495 --> 18:36.663
from escaping from East Berlin
into West Berlin.

18:36.665 --> 18:39.733
There were many cases
of people being shot

18:39.735 --> 18:42.335
as they were trying to leave
one side of the city.

18:42.337 --> 18:44.805
It was a very, very
dangerous time.

18:44.807 --> 18:47.541
♪♪

18:47.543 --> 18:50.143
WILDMAN: But Dieterling refuses
to be deterred.

18:50.145 --> 18:54.548
Leaving East Berlin is the
only way for a better life.

18:54.550 --> 18:56.049
WILDMAN:
And Dieterling's job,

18:56.051 --> 18:59.119
driving passenger trains
for the East German Railway,

18:59.121 --> 19:01.722
offers him a unique view
of the obstacle

19:01.724 --> 19:04.124
and a chance
to break through it.

19:04.126 --> 19:06.960
One day, he discovers
something extraordinary.

19:06.962 --> 19:09.296
There is still a set
of railway tracks

19:09.298 --> 19:11.298
connecting East and West Berlin.

19:11.300 --> 19:14.334
What the East Germans had done
was seal off those tracks

19:14.336 --> 19:16.636
with what was, at the time,
quite flimsy barriers --

19:16.638 --> 19:19.439
fences and barbed wire
and things like that.

19:19.441 --> 19:22.175
But actually,
the opportunity did exist

19:22.177 --> 19:25.212
to continue straight through
those flimsy barriers

19:25.214 --> 19:28.181
and break your way,
theoretically, into the West.

19:30.385 --> 19:32.686
WILDMAN:
Dieterling hatches a bold plan.

19:32.688 --> 19:35.789
He will load his family
and friends onto his train

19:35.791 --> 19:39.392
and crash the locomotive
straight through the barrier.

19:39.394 --> 19:41.328
He was not just
risking his own life,

19:41.330 --> 19:43.597
but he was risking
the life of his wife,

19:43.599 --> 19:47.501
of his small children, of all
of his friends and family.

19:47.503 --> 19:51.004
♪♪

19:51.006 --> 19:54.307
WILDMAN: On the night
of December 5th, 1961,

19:54.309 --> 19:55.909
Dieterling quietly sneaks

19:55.911 --> 19:59.312
24 family members
and friends onto the train.

19:59.314 --> 20:01.915
He then sets out
full steam ahead.

20:01.917 --> 20:05.418
ALCOCK: This was Dieterling's
one and only chance.

20:05.420 --> 20:08.488
If this failed,
there was no coming back.

20:08.490 --> 20:10.490
[ Whistle blaring ]

20:15.730 --> 20:20.066
It's December 5th, 1961,
in East Berlin.

20:20.068 --> 20:22.435
A railroad engineer
named Harry Dieterling

20:22.437 --> 20:25.004
is about to make
the journey of his life.

20:25.006 --> 20:28.508
He means to smash his train
through the Berlin Wall

20:28.510 --> 20:30.810
and find freedom in the West.

20:30.812 --> 20:33.413
It's a bold plan,
but will it work?

20:35.483 --> 20:36.682
As Dieterling's train

20:36.684 --> 20:39.318
approaches its final
scheduled stop,

20:39.320 --> 20:40.620
instead of slowing,

20:40.622 --> 20:42.688
he accelerates
towards the barrier

20:42.690 --> 20:44.490
separating East from West.

20:46.394 --> 20:49.896
ALCOCK:
He must've had adrenaline
coursing through his veins --

20:49.898 --> 20:54.867
a mixture of fear,
of terror, of anticipation.

20:54.869 --> 20:58.571
♪♪

20:58.573 --> 21:00.206
WILDMAN:
The border guards are helpless

21:00.208 --> 21:02.842
as the train
barrels down the tracks.

21:02.844 --> 21:06.078
Dieterling's train
hurtles into the barrier

21:06.080 --> 21:09.081
and crashes safely through
to the western side.

21:09.083 --> 21:13.586
♪♪

21:13.588 --> 21:16.389
ALCOCK: Dieterling must've felt,
in that moment,

21:16.391 --> 21:19.358
I imagine, euphoric
that he managed to pull this off

21:19.360 --> 21:21.928
really completely unscathed.

21:21.930 --> 21:23.162
WILDMAN:
Not surprisingly,

21:23.164 --> 21:26.199
the very next day,
the barricade is sealed,

21:26.201 --> 21:28.568
and Dieterling's
ambitious bid for freedom

21:28.570 --> 21:30.603
makes international headlines.

21:30.605 --> 21:32.572
ALCOCK:
This escape was so brave

21:32.574 --> 21:36.375
and was so dramatic
in its details and its content

21:36.377 --> 21:39.612
that it actually became
a worldwide news story.

21:39.614 --> 21:43.449
And really, he was held up as
something of a hero at the time.

21:43.451 --> 21:44.617
WILDMAN:
Dieterling and his family

21:44.619 --> 21:47.019
start a new life
in West Germany.

21:47.021 --> 21:50.523
The Berlin Wall remains in place
for nearly three decades,

21:50.525 --> 21:52.725
until it comes down in 1989.

21:52.727 --> 21:55.294
♪♪

21:55.296 --> 21:58.097
Today, this model of
a train track and barrier

21:58.099 --> 22:00.700
is on display at
the Checkpoint Charlie Museum

22:00.702 --> 22:02.301
in Berlin, Germany.

22:02.303 --> 22:04.470
It illustrates the brave railman

22:04.472 --> 22:06.105
who broke through to freedom.

22:06.107 --> 22:09.742
♪♪

22:09.744 --> 22:13.779
Located in the Florida Keys,
the town of Islamorada

22:13.781 --> 22:17.350
boasts the country's only
living coral barrier reef.

22:17.352 --> 22:20.653
Divers can admire
the 500 or so species of fish

22:20.655 --> 22:22.455
that reside in these waters

22:22.457 --> 22:27.159
and swim beside a sunken 1960s'
freighter named the<i> Eagle.</i>

22:27.161 --> 22:28.895
And one area institution

22:28.897 --> 22:31.564
celebrates this world
beneath the waves --

22:31.566 --> 22:33.432
the History of Diving Museum.

22:33.434 --> 22:35.968
♪♪

22:35.970 --> 22:37.537
The collection includes

22:37.539 --> 22:39.539
the first underwater
metal detector --

22:39.541 --> 22:42.742
invented in the 1950s --

22:42.744 --> 22:46.078
an oxygen-supplying device
known as a rebreather

22:46.080 --> 22:49.882
used in marine
cave explorations,

22:49.884 --> 22:51.350
and a specialized suit

22:51.352 --> 22:55.555
capable of protecting divers
at depths of nearly 1,000 feet.

22:57.992 --> 23:01.193
But none of these
subnautical marvels would exist

23:01.195 --> 23:03.763
if not for one peculiar piece.

23:03.765 --> 23:06.732
COSTELLO: The artifact
is expertly cast and soldered

23:06.734 --> 23:10.503
into copper plates
and shaped into a dome.

23:10.505 --> 23:14.974
Its surface is covered with
glass, rivets, and metal bars.

23:14.976 --> 23:17.009
There are a pair of
ports in the back,

23:17.011 --> 23:19.111
and one can connect
to a long rubber hose.

23:19.113 --> 23:23.382
♪♪

23:23.384 --> 23:26.619
WILDMAN: This item recalls
a disaster on land

23:26.621 --> 23:29.655
that shaped the future
of undersea exploration.

23:29.657 --> 23:31.924
COSTELLO: This is a story
of a sailor, a suit of armor,

23:31.926 --> 23:34.060
and an invention
that changed the world.

23:34.062 --> 23:40.166
♪♪

23:40.168 --> 23:43.703
WILDMAN: It's the 1820s
on the east coast of England.

23:43.705 --> 23:46.973
After several years at sea
as a merchant sailor,

23:46.975 --> 23:48.874
21-year-old John Deane

23:48.876 --> 23:51.811
has returned home
to the town of Whitstable.

23:51.813 --> 23:55.948
John Deane was brave, bold,
and he had become fearless.

23:55.950 --> 23:58.618
♪♪

23:58.620 --> 24:00.519
WILDMAN: Yet the young sailor
is about to find

24:00.521 --> 24:04.123
that his biggest challenge
won't take place at sea,

24:04.125 --> 24:05.992
but right next-door.

24:05.994 --> 24:07.627
One day, Deane is at home

24:07.629 --> 24:10.129
when he sees plumes
of smoke and fire

24:10.131 --> 24:12.632
billowing from
his neighbor's farm.

24:12.634 --> 24:14.700
COSTELLO:
Deane did not hesitate to act.

24:14.702 --> 24:17.203
He rushed out of his own house,

24:17.205 --> 24:18.904
and he went to his neighbor's

24:18.906 --> 24:22.074
to see what he could do to help.

24:22.076 --> 24:25.311
WILDMAN: When he gets there,
he finds his neighbor in panic.

24:25.313 --> 24:26.779
The family's prized horses

24:26.781 --> 24:30.149
are trapped inside
the burning barn.

24:30.151 --> 24:32.451
Reaching them seems impossible.

24:32.453 --> 24:34.854
♪♪

24:34.856 --> 24:38.057
The smoke was too thick to
even breathe in the space.

24:38.059 --> 24:40.760
WILDMAN: It's too dangerous
to risk going in,

24:40.762 --> 24:42.928
so Deane tries
to extinguish the fire

24:42.930 --> 24:45.998
using pails of water
from a nearby pond.

24:46.000 --> 24:48.367
But his efforts are in vain.

24:48.369 --> 24:52.104
Then, just as all seems lost,
the fire brigade arrives

24:52.106 --> 24:54.407
with the equipment needed
to fight the blaze.

24:56.411 --> 24:58.944
COSTELLO: They arrived with
a hose and a pump,

24:58.946 --> 25:02.848
and this seemed to be a solution
that would probably work.

25:02.850 --> 25:04.550
WILDMAN:
They spray the barn down,

25:04.552 --> 25:06.619
but the smoke only grows.

25:06.621 --> 25:08.587
Time is running out
for the trapped horses...

25:08.589 --> 25:10.022
[ Horse neighing ]

25:10.024 --> 25:13.192
...so Deane frantically searches
for anything that might help.

25:13.194 --> 25:14.894
♪♪

25:14.896 --> 25:17.963
Then he sees something
that gives him an idea.

25:17.965 --> 25:19.765
In the doorway of
the farmer's home

25:19.767 --> 25:23.436
stands a medieval suit of armor.

25:23.438 --> 25:26.272
He reached up,
took the helmet off the armor,

25:26.274 --> 25:30.543
tucked it beneath his arm,
and rushed outside.

25:30.545 --> 25:33.145
What Deane does next will
not only save the day,

25:33.147 --> 25:35.081
but echo through the ages.

25:35.083 --> 25:39.251
♪♪

25:43.240 --> 25:45.640
It's the 1820s in England.

25:45.642 --> 25:48.710
A fire has broken out
at a remote farmhouse.

25:48.712 --> 25:50.746
The stables are
filled with smoke,

25:50.748 --> 25:53.115
and the horses are in peril.

25:53.117 --> 25:56.651
But a young man named John Deane
is about to save the day

25:56.653 --> 25:59.921
and change the course
of history in the process.

26:01.792 --> 26:03.358
Deane tells the fire brigade

26:03.360 --> 26:05.761
that he wants to attach
one of their water hoses

26:05.763 --> 26:08.530
to the inside
of the medieval helmet.

26:08.532 --> 26:11.032
But rather than pumping water
through the hose,

26:11.034 --> 26:14.736
he asks the fire brigade
to pump in air.

26:14.738 --> 26:17.439
By using the hose
to pump air into the helmet,

26:17.441 --> 26:20.041
it would be providing
him with fresh air

26:20.043 --> 26:22.110
in this haze of smoke.

26:24.181 --> 26:26.281
WILDMAN: Deane puts this
improvised apparatus

26:26.283 --> 26:29.951
on his head and bravely
enters the burning barn.

26:29.953 --> 26:32.521
COSTELLO: Even as smoke
filtered around him,

26:32.523 --> 26:36.191
the fresh air from the pump
was coming up into that helmet,

26:36.193 --> 26:38.927
and he found he was
able to breathe.

26:38.929 --> 26:39.995
WILDMAN: One by one,

26:39.997 --> 26:42.831
he leads the terrified
horses to safety.

26:42.833 --> 26:45.801
♪♪

26:45.803 --> 26:49.037
COSTELLO: As Deane staggered
out of the stable,

26:49.039 --> 26:51.573
he was met with the praise
of all of his neighbors

26:51.575 --> 26:53.108
for his act of heroism.

26:53.110 --> 26:56.111
♪♪

26:56.113 --> 26:58.180
WILDMAN:
But the story doesn't end there.

26:58.182 --> 26:59.681
After the ordeal,

26:59.683 --> 27:02.684
Deane can't help but think
of his days as a sailor

27:02.686 --> 27:04.886
and wonders if
his breathing contraption

27:04.888 --> 27:06.455
could be useful at sea.

27:06.457 --> 27:08.990
Deane's fire rescue
whet his appetite

27:08.992 --> 27:13.295
and inspired him in new ways
to use his invention.

27:13.297 --> 27:14.830
WILDMAN:
Deane eventually constructs

27:14.832 --> 27:18.133
a new version of
his makeshift invention.

27:18.135 --> 27:20.702
He molds a helmet
made of copper.

27:20.704 --> 27:22.704
In place of
narrow eye slits,

27:22.706 --> 27:25.140
he installs
glass windows.

27:25.142 --> 27:27.976
Then he affixes two nozzles
on the back

27:27.978 --> 27:30.912
where hoses can be connected
to pump air in and out.

27:30.914 --> 27:33.482
♪♪

27:33.484 --> 27:36.117
When he's finished,
he has the world's first

27:36.119 --> 27:38.420
underwater diving helmet.

27:38.422 --> 27:41.223
COSTELLO: Dean's invention
became the prototype

27:41.225 --> 27:45.126
for the iconic diving helmet
that we know today.

27:45.128 --> 27:47.796
WILDMAN: John Dean's design
serves as the standard

27:47.798 --> 27:50.932
for divers
for the next 150 years

27:50.934 --> 27:53.902
and is the clear precursor
to the devices used today.

27:53.904 --> 27:58.173
♪♪

27:58.175 --> 28:00.642
And this replica
of his original diving helmet

28:00.644 --> 28:03.979
sits on display at
the History of Diving Museum

28:03.981 --> 28:06.047
in Islamorado, Florida.

28:06.049 --> 28:08.383
It recalls
the blaze-battling sailor

28:08.385 --> 28:11.887
whose clever innovation
opened up a new frontier.

28:11.889 --> 28:16.391
♪♪

28:16.393 --> 28:19.728
A navigational antenna
from the 1940s,

28:19.730 --> 28:24.299
a host of military vehicles
that span the 20th century,

28:24.301 --> 28:27.903
and a preserved nuclear bunker
built during the Cold War

28:27.905 --> 28:29.471
are just a few of the highlights

28:29.473 --> 28:32.941
at the InfoAge Science History
Museum and Learning Center

28:32.943 --> 28:34.175
in Wall, New Jersey.

28:36.346 --> 28:39.381
But among these examples
of war-time technology

28:39.383 --> 28:42.951
is one item that's found
its place in everyday life.

28:42.953 --> 28:45.186
FITZPATRICK:
The artifact is 7 inches long

28:45.188 --> 28:47.022
by 8 1/2 inches high.

28:47.024 --> 28:50.125
It consists of a wooden box
with wires coming out of it.

28:50.127 --> 28:54.229
It has metal and glass,
tubes, knobs, and switches.

28:54.231 --> 28:57.165
This item is almost
a hundred years old.

28:59.269 --> 29:02.037
This 1920s' radio
was at the center

29:02.039 --> 29:06.641
of one man's ambitious idea to
change the way the world sounds.

29:06.643 --> 29:09.444
This is a story about
innovation, inspiration,

29:09.446 --> 29:10.679
and invention.

29:10.681 --> 29:15.383
♪♪

29:15.385 --> 29:17.652
WILDMAN:
It's 1921.

29:17.654 --> 29:19.321
It's a new era
of convenience

29:19.323 --> 29:22.757
and revolutionary technology
for American consumers.

29:22.759 --> 29:26.328
From coast to coast, companies
cash in with appliances

29:26.330 --> 29:30.265
like refrigerators,
toasters, and dishwashers.

29:30.267 --> 29:32.767
♪♪

29:32.769 --> 29:35.003
One man looking to
get in on the action

29:35.005 --> 29:39.007
is a 30-year-old businessman
named David Sarnoff.

29:39.009 --> 29:41.142
FITZPATRICK:
David Sarnoff was a visionary.

29:41.144 --> 29:43.445
He was tenacious. He was bold.

29:43.447 --> 29:46.514
He was an innovator,
and he was a self-starter.

29:46.516 --> 29:48.316
WILDMAN: Sarnoff works
for a company called

29:48.318 --> 29:50.585
The Radio Corporation
of America,

29:50.587 --> 29:53.288
better known today as RCA.

29:53.290 --> 29:56.091
He thinks RCA can profit
by rebranding

29:56.093 --> 29:59.561
a piece of military equipment
for in-home use --

29:59.563 --> 30:00.629
the radio.

30:00.631 --> 30:02.497
Up to this point,
it had only been used

30:02.499 --> 30:04.032
for two-way communication.

30:04.034 --> 30:06.735
♪♪

30:06.737 --> 30:09.170
WILDMAN: The radio had been
used during World War I

30:09.172 --> 30:12.874
to relay information
to planes, ships, and bases.

30:12.876 --> 30:14.576
But with the conflict long over,

30:14.578 --> 30:17.712
there aren't too many
applications for the technology.

30:17.714 --> 30:19.481
FITZPATRICK: The radio had been
a war-time tool.

30:19.483 --> 30:22.217
But after the war,
nobody knew what to do with it.

30:22.219 --> 30:24.386
WILDMAN: Sarnoff has an inkling
that this device

30:24.388 --> 30:27.389
could be repurposed to
offer regular Americans

30:27.391 --> 30:29.824
news, music, and
other entertainment.

30:31.361 --> 30:33.595
FITZPATRICK: Sarnoff thinks
radio can be like libraries --

30:33.597 --> 30:37.065
a place for people to come
and get timely information.

30:37.067 --> 30:40.669
WILDMAN: He presents his idea
to RCA executives.

30:40.671 --> 30:43.271
But his bosses aren't onboard.

30:43.273 --> 30:46.941
When RCA heard Sarnoff's idea,
they were skeptical.

30:46.943 --> 30:48.677
WILDMAN: The company
won't back the proposal

30:48.679 --> 30:51.446
because there's nothing for
the public to listen to.

30:51.448 --> 30:53.214
No content exists.

30:55.385 --> 30:58.186
But that doesn't stop
the bold businessman.

30:58.188 --> 30:59.621
FITZPATRICK:
Sarnoff was determined.

30:59.623 --> 31:01.990
He was certain
radio had a future.

31:01.992 --> 31:04.559
He needed to find a way to
get the public interested

31:04.561 --> 31:05.827
in buying radios.

31:05.829 --> 31:09.831
WILDMAN: So how will Sarnoff
tune America into radio?

31:09.833 --> 31:12.734
ANNOUNCER:
<i>The heavyweight champion</i>
<i>of the world...</i>

31:12.736 --> 31:13.902
[ Cheering ]

31:17.881 --> 31:20.648
It's the 1920s in New York City.

31:20.650 --> 31:23.451
Businessman David Sarnoff
has an idea

31:23.453 --> 31:25.720
he believes
could change history.

31:25.722 --> 31:27.255
He thinks that an obscure piece

31:27.257 --> 31:29.557
of World War I
military equipment

31:29.559 --> 31:32.994
could find a new lease on life
in American homes.

31:32.996 --> 31:34.062
Its name?

31:34.064 --> 31:35.530
The radio.

31:35.532 --> 31:38.266
But how will he convince
a skeptical public

31:38.268 --> 31:41.503
that this machine will
make waves across the country?

31:43.306 --> 31:45.740
David Sarnoff is trying
to develop an audience

31:45.742 --> 31:49.644
for the radio
when, in the spring of 1921,

31:49.646 --> 31:51.846
he hears about
an upcoming boxing match

31:51.848 --> 31:55.283
between Jack Dempsey
and George Carpentier

31:55.285 --> 31:58.353
set to take place just outside
of New York City.

31:58.355 --> 32:01.055
The bout has
the whole country buzzing.

32:01.057 --> 32:03.158
Jack Dempsey was the heavyweight
champion of the world,

32:03.160 --> 32:04.225
and he was defending his title

32:04.227 --> 32:06.461
against challenger
George Carpentier.

32:06.463 --> 32:08.563
It was billed as
"The Fight of the Century."

32:08.565 --> 32:10.732
When tickets for
the match go on sale,

32:10.734 --> 32:13.234
all 90,000 sell out,

32:13.236 --> 32:16.738
and this gives Sarnoff
a brilliant idea.

32:16.740 --> 32:18.773
FITZPATRICK: Sarnoff believed
The Fight of the Century

32:18.775 --> 32:20.375
was a match made in Heaven.

32:20.377 --> 32:22.444
The newspapers are writing
about it every day.

32:22.446 --> 32:24.579
The public wanted
to hear about it.

32:24.581 --> 32:27.315
WILDMAN: Sarnoff realizes
that there are countless people

32:27.317 --> 32:29.984
who don't want
to miss out on the action.

32:29.986 --> 32:32.854
So he comes up with a plan
to broadcast the fight

32:32.856 --> 32:34.088
over the radio.

32:34.090 --> 32:36.357
He'll offer people
the chance to hear the match

32:36.359 --> 32:39.227
at listening locations
along the East Coast.

32:39.229 --> 32:41.196
If it works,
he just might be able

32:41.198 --> 32:46.267
to prove radio's potential
to his skeptical bosses at RCA.

32:46.269 --> 32:48.036
FITZPATRICK: Sarnoff knew
this was his big chance,

32:48.038 --> 32:50.205
and he wasn't gonna
go down without a fight.

32:50.207 --> 32:51.706
WILDMAN:
In the days before the match,

32:51.708 --> 32:54.108
Sarnoff sets up
a broadcast transmitter

32:54.110 --> 32:56.311
inside the boxing venue.

32:56.313 --> 32:59.747
Then he distributes radios
to bar and theater owners

32:59.749 --> 33:01.516
all over the East Coast,

33:01.518 --> 33:04.052
and they help publicize
the broadcast.

33:04.054 --> 33:06.454
Lastly, Sarnoff hires
an announcer

33:06.456 --> 33:08.756
to narrate the event
for the listening audience.

33:08.758 --> 33:10.825
♪♪

33:10.827 --> 33:12.126
ANNOUNCER:
<i>Round 1, coming up...</i>

33:12.128 --> 33:15.830
WILDMAN: On July 2nd, 1921,
the fight between Dempsey

33:15.832 --> 33:18.066
and Carpentier begins.

33:18.068 --> 33:19.334
[ Bell dings ]

33:19.336 --> 33:21.236
WILDMAN: Sarnoff listens as
the presenter gives

33:21.238 --> 33:24.906
a thrilling play-by-play
of the entire fight.

33:24.908 --> 33:26.174
But he can only wonder

33:26.176 --> 33:28.543
how many people
are actually tuned in.

33:28.545 --> 33:31.679
♪♪

33:31.681 --> 33:35.216
There was no way to measure
audiences like there is today.

33:35.218 --> 33:36.885
WILDMAN:
But in the days after the fight,

33:36.887 --> 33:38.820
something remarkable happens.

33:38.822 --> 33:41.189
FITZPATRICK: Letters from
listeners pour into RCA

33:41.191 --> 33:43.491
demanding more sporting events
be carried.

33:43.493 --> 33:46.361
WILDMAN: It's estimated
that 300,000 people

33:46.363 --> 33:48.863
listened to Sarnoff's broadcast.

33:48.865 --> 33:51.833
It's just the news
Sarnoff has been waiting for.

33:51.835 --> 33:55.069
His stunt proves to RCA
and the American public

33:55.071 --> 33:57.872
that radio is the wave
of the future.

33:57.874 --> 34:00.174
This was a game-changer
for the radio industry.

34:00.176 --> 34:01.809
Sales took off.

34:01.811 --> 34:03.711
Everyone wanted radio
in their living room.

34:03.713 --> 34:06.848
Sarnoff must have felt elated.

34:06.850 --> 34:10.552
WILDMAN:
The company begins manufacturing
radios for home use

34:10.554 --> 34:14.622
and launches a radio network
to fill the air time.

34:14.624 --> 34:17.625
David Sarnoff goes on
to become president of RCA

34:17.627 --> 34:21.362
and pioneers another
revolutionary technology --

34:21.364 --> 34:22.864
television.

34:22.866 --> 34:25.133
FITZPATRICK:
Sarnoff's name is part
of broadcasting history.

34:25.135 --> 34:27.368
He's included on the list
of one of the greatest

34:27.370 --> 34:29.070
20th-century
American businessmen.

34:29.072 --> 34:32.273
♪♪

34:32.275 --> 34:36.444
WILDMAN:
Today, this early model RCA
radio remains in the collection

34:36.446 --> 34:39.914
of the Info Age Science History
Museum and Learning Center

34:39.916 --> 34:41.749
in Wall, New Jersey.

34:41.751 --> 34:44.886
It's a lasting reminder
of how one man got America

34:44.888 --> 34:46.888
riding the wave of radio.

34:46.890 --> 34:52.393
♪♪

34:52.395 --> 34:54.529
New Haven, Connecticut.

34:54.531 --> 34:58.366
In the 1920s, on the elegant
grounds of Yale University,

34:58.368 --> 35:01.502
one of America's favorite
pastimes was conceived.

35:01.504 --> 35:03.771
Students would take breaks
from studying

35:03.773 --> 35:06.474
by tossing around
empty pie tins

35:06.476 --> 35:09.243
manufactured by
a local pie company called...

35:09.245 --> 35:10.979
Frisbie.

35:10.981 --> 35:12.947
And what started
as a campus craze

35:12.949 --> 35:15.283
eventually turned into
a popular sport

35:15.285 --> 35:17.485
that's still played today.

35:17.487 --> 35:20.054
But a more intellectual
pursuit can be found at

35:20.056 --> 35:23.958
the University's Beinecke Rare
Book and Manuscript Library.

35:25.462 --> 35:28.663
Here, visitors can see some
of the earliest illustrated

35:28.665 --> 35:32.000
tales of King Arthur and the
Knights of the Round Table,

35:32.002 --> 35:33.701
astrological star charts

35:33.703 --> 35:37.472
made by English astrologers
in the 1500s,

35:37.474 --> 35:41.509
and stunning pictures of
rare birds drawn in the 1830s

35:41.511 --> 35:44.579
by the famed ornithologist
John James Audubon.

35:46.683 --> 35:49.884
And among these antique works
is an elaborate tome

35:49.886 --> 35:54.055
that many regard as the most
important book in the world.

35:54.057 --> 35:56.391
JAMES:
The item is about 15 inches long

35:56.393 --> 35:59.360
and is over 550 years old.

35:59.362 --> 36:02.263
It is comprised of 1,282 pages

36:02.265 --> 36:04.265
bound between
two leather covers.

36:04.267 --> 36:07.101
♪♪

36:07.103 --> 36:10.104
WILDMAN: This ancient book
marked a historic first,

36:10.106 --> 36:13.641
but few know the incredible
story of its origins.

36:13.643 --> 36:16.310
JAMES:
This is the story of one man
who changed the world

36:16.312 --> 36:17.979
one page at a time.

36:17.981 --> 36:22.517
♪♪

36:22.519 --> 36:24.519
WILDMAN: Following the fall
of the Roman Empire

36:24.521 --> 36:26.120
in the 5th century,

36:26.122 --> 36:29.757
Western Europe entered a period
known as the Dark Ages.

36:29.759 --> 36:32.627
As the memory
of Roman civilization faded,

36:32.629 --> 36:36.230
the tribes of Northern Europe
descended into barbarity.

36:36.232 --> 36:39.000
Practically the only sources
of written culture

36:39.002 --> 36:40.601
are religious texts,

36:40.603 --> 36:43.271
painstakingly transcribed
by monks.

36:43.273 --> 36:45.606
JAMES: Books took
a very long time to write.

36:45.608 --> 36:49.444
They were created by scribes
writing by hand.

36:49.446 --> 36:52.647
WILDMAN: As a result, books
are extremely expensive

36:52.649 --> 36:54.515
and only accessible
to scholars

36:54.517 --> 36:55.917
and the wealthy elite.

36:55.919 --> 36:58.219
JAMES: Books were
very rare in this period.

36:58.221 --> 37:01.389
They were not something that
were common for most people.

37:01.391 --> 37:04.125
♪♪

37:04.127 --> 37:06.928
WILDMAN: But in the late
1440s in Germany,

37:06.930 --> 37:09.964
a man comes along
who changes everything --

37:09.966 --> 37:12.567
inventor Johannes Gutenberg.

37:12.569 --> 37:15.737
JAMES: Gutenberg seems to have
been extremely imaginative.

37:15.739 --> 37:18.973
He thought of
new business ideas

37:18.975 --> 37:20.742
pretty much continually.

37:20.744 --> 37:23.144
WILDMAN: Gutenberg sees
a money-making opportunity

37:23.146 --> 37:24.545
in books.

37:24.547 --> 37:28.816
The question is how to make more
of them cheaper and faster.

37:28.818 --> 37:30.618
So he imagines a machine

37:30.620 --> 37:33.421
that won't rely on
handwriting at all --

37:33.423 --> 37:35.323
a printing press.

37:36.993 --> 37:39.427
JAMES: Gutenberg had to
figure out a way

37:39.429 --> 37:43.097
to bring letters together
on the printed page

37:43.099 --> 37:45.566
in the way that a scribe
would do in writing.

37:45.568 --> 37:47.101
He really wanted
to create something

37:47.103 --> 37:49.036
that was just phenomenal,

37:49.038 --> 37:50.638
that had never been seen.

37:50.640 --> 37:52.607
WILDMAN: Gutenberg conceives
of a contraption

37:52.609 --> 37:54.475
that will hold
the letters of the alphabet

37:54.477 --> 37:57.712
carved onto tiny pieces
of metal.

37:57.714 --> 37:59.747
He builds a frame
for the machine

37:59.749 --> 38:02.850
and then creates blocks of
letters that can be arranged

38:02.852 --> 38:06.687
to form any word
and reused over and over again.

38:06.689 --> 38:09.991
So, a page of text would be
built up letter by letter,

38:09.993 --> 38:12.193
line by line.

38:12.195 --> 38:15.763
WILDMAN: When finished printing
multiple copies of one page,

38:15.765 --> 38:18.266
an operator could simply
rearrange the letters

38:18.268 --> 38:19.867
and print the next.

38:19.869 --> 38:22.303
To serve as
his pressing apparatus,

38:22.305 --> 38:25.006
Gutenberg adapts
an existing tool.

38:25.008 --> 38:27.441
JAMES: Gutenberg's press
seems to have been based

38:27.443 --> 38:29.644
on a wine screw
that would be used

38:29.646 --> 38:32.280
for pressing grapes
and making wine.

38:32.282 --> 38:33.714
WILDMAN:
With the machine assembled,

38:33.716 --> 38:35.516
he gives it a test run.

38:35.518 --> 38:39.320
He lays a page of block text
and coats it with ink.

38:39.322 --> 38:42.523
Then he presses it
against a sheet of parchment.

38:42.525 --> 38:44.625
But when Gutenberg
holds up the results,

38:44.627 --> 38:46.994
something has gone
horribly wrong.

38:46.996 --> 38:49.430
The page is nothing
but a hideous splodge

38:49.432 --> 38:51.799
of blotches and smudges.

38:51.801 --> 38:55.469
So how will he fix his invention
and rewrite history?

38:55.471 --> 38:58.773
♪♪

39:02.812 --> 39:05.646
It's the 15th century
in Germany.

39:05.648 --> 39:07.949
Johannes Gutenberg
has just invented

39:07.951 --> 39:09.984
a revolutionary contraption --

39:09.986 --> 39:11.819
the printing press.

39:11.821 --> 39:15.289
But when he tests it out,
the results are a mess.

39:15.291 --> 39:19.360
So how will Gutenberg fix his
device and rewrite history?

39:21.264 --> 39:24.665
When Gutenberg takes
a closer look at the test page,

39:24.667 --> 39:27.435
he realizes the problem
isn't with the press,

39:27.437 --> 39:29.237
but with the ink.

39:29.239 --> 39:32.106
JAMES: Ink that scribes used
was water-based.

39:32.108 --> 39:35.810
And it essentially dyed the
material that it was touching.

39:35.812 --> 39:38.212
WILDMAN: This ink is fine
for hand lettering,

39:38.214 --> 39:41.048
but too runny for Gutenberg's
printing press.

39:41.050 --> 39:42.517
To make his machine work,

39:42.519 --> 39:44.752
he must create
a whole new formula.

39:44.754 --> 39:46.554
Gutenberg needed
an oil-based ink

39:46.556 --> 39:48.656
that would accrue
to the page.

39:50.560 --> 39:52.760
WILDMAN:
Gutenberg tests various new inks

39:52.762 --> 39:55.430
before finally settling
on a mixture of ingredients

39:55.432 --> 39:57.532
that just might work.

39:57.534 --> 40:01.436
It was a combination
of linseed oil and carbon

40:01.438 --> 40:03.638
taken from burning substances.

40:03.640 --> 40:08.876
It had a glossy sheen and
was an entirely new composition.

40:08.878 --> 40:11.546
Gutenberg applies
his new ink to the letters,

40:11.548 --> 40:15.583
laying down a sheet of paper,
and lowers the press.

40:15.585 --> 40:17.752
To his delight,
when he raises it,

40:17.754 --> 40:19.821
he has a perfectly
printed sheet.

40:22.125 --> 40:25.226
JAMES: The culmination of
Gutenberg's work

40:25.228 --> 40:28.796
was the creation of
a mechanical printing press

40:28.798 --> 40:31.532
that could
produce text repeatedly

40:31.534 --> 40:35.036
without relying on the work of
individual scribes.

40:35.038 --> 40:37.705
WILDMAN: Gutenberg decides
that his first major project

40:37.707 --> 40:40.741
will be to copy one of the
most highly sought after texts

40:40.743 --> 40:44.679
in the world -- the Holy Bible.

40:44.681 --> 40:47.215
JAMES:
The Bible would be a showpiece.

40:47.217 --> 40:50.017
It would be
something spectacular

40:50.019 --> 40:52.119
that would be
guaranteed to sell.

40:52.121 --> 40:55.890
WILDMAN: In 1455,
he prints about 180 copies

40:55.892 --> 40:57.425
of the Latin Bible.

40:57.427 --> 40:59.060
They sell immediately

40:59.062 --> 41:02.230
and begin a new era
for the printed word.

41:02.232 --> 41:05.266
Within decades,
print was a common technology

41:05.268 --> 41:06.634
across Europe.

41:06.636 --> 41:09.370
♪♪

41:09.372 --> 41:12.473
WILDMAN: Suddenly,
a brand-new world opens up.

41:12.475 --> 41:15.877
Because books are cheaper,
more people learn to read.

41:15.879 --> 41:19.180
And this jump-starts
a cultural revolution.

41:19.182 --> 41:21.549
JAMES:
In inventing the printing press,

41:21.551 --> 41:25.086
Gutenberg made a way to
reach a much broader audience.

41:25.088 --> 41:26.254
We're still living

41:26.256 --> 41:28.589
in the world
that Gutenberg created.

41:28.591 --> 41:30.658
WILDMAN:
Today, this Gutenberg Bible,

41:30.660 --> 41:34.462
one of only 49 copies
known to exist, is on display

41:34.464 --> 41:37.331
at the Beinecke Rare Book
and Manuscript Library

41:37.333 --> 41:39.333
in New Haven, Connecticut.

41:39.335 --> 41:41.302
It recalls how one inventive man

41:41.304 --> 41:44.105
imprinted his name
into the annals of history.

41:44.107 --> 41:47.208
♪♪

41:47.210 --> 41:51.512
From a circus brawl,
to a train trip to freedom,

41:51.514 --> 41:56.984
an underwater invention,
to The Battle of the Sexes,

41:56.986 --> 42:00.588
I'm Don Wildman and these are
the "Mysteries at the Museum."
